# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: restructuredtext
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] A **lightweight markup language** (**LML**), also termed a **simple** or **humane markup language**, is a markup language with simple, unobtrusive syntax.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] It is designed to be easy to write using any generic text editor and easy to read in its raw form.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] It is used in applications where it may be necessary to read the raw document and the final rendered output.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] For instance, a person downloading a software library might prefer to read the documentation in a text editor rather than a web browser.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] Another use for such languages is to provide for data entry in web-based publishing, as in blogs and wikis, where the input interface is a simple text box.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] The server software then converts the input into a common document markup language like HTML.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] Lightweight markup languages were originally used on text-only displays which could not display characters in italics or bold, so informal methods to convey this information had to be developed.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] This formatting choice was naturally carried forth to plain-text email communications.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] Console browsers may also resort to similar display conventions.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] In 1986 international standard SGML provided facilities to define and parse lightweight markup languages using grammars and tag implication.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] The 1998 W3C XML is a profile of SGML that omits these facilities.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] However, no SGML document type definition (DTD) for any of the languages listed below is known.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] Lightweight markup languages can be categorized by their tag types.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] Most languages distinguish between markup for lines or blocks and for shorter spans of texts, but some only support inline markup.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] Some markup languages are tailored for a specific purpose, such as documenting computer code (e.g., POD, reST, RD) or being converted to a certain output format (usually HTML or LaTeX) and nothing else, others are more general in application.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] This includes whether they are oriented on textual presentation or on data serialization.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] Presentation oriented languages include AsciiDoc, atx, BBCode, Creole, Crossmark, Djot, Epytext, Haml, JsonML, MakeDoc, Markdown, Org-mode, POD (Perl), reST (Python), RD (Ruby), Setext, SiSU, SPIP, Xupl, Texy!, Textile, txt2tags, UDO and Wikitext.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] Data serialization oriented languages include Curl (homoiconic, but also reads JSON; every object serializes), JSON, and YAML.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] Markdown's own syntax does not support class attributes or id attributes; however, since Markdown supports the inclusion of native HTML code, these features can be implemented using direct HTML.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] txt2tags' own syntax does not support class attributes or id attributes; however, since txt2tags supports inclusion of native HTML code in tagged areas, these features can be implemented using direct HTML when saving to an HTML target.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] DokuWiki does not support HTML import natively, but HTML to DokuWiki converters and importers exist and are mentioned in the official documentation.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] DokuWiki does not support class or id attributes, but can be set up to support HTML code, which does support both features.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] HTML code support was built-in before release 2023-04-04.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] In later versions, HTML code support can be achieved through plug-ins, though it is discouraged.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] Although usually documented as yielding italic and bold text, most lightweight markup processors output semantic HTML elements `em` and `strong` instead.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] Monospaced text may either result in semantic `code` or presentational `tt` elements.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] Few languages make a distinction, e.g., Textile, or allow the user to configure the output easily, e.g., Texy.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] LMLs sometimes differ for multi-word markup where some require the markup characters to replace the inter-word spaces (*infix*).
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] Some languages require one character as prefix and suffix, others need two or even three, or support both with slightly different meaning, e.g., different levels of emphasis.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] Gemtext does not have any inline formatting, monospaced text (called preformatted text in the context of Gemtext) must have the opening and closing ``` on their own lines.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] In HTML, text is emphasized with the `<em>` and `<strong>` element types, whereas `<i>` and `<b>` traditionally mark up text to be italicized or bold-faced, respectively.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] Microsoft Word and Outlook, and accordingly other word processors and mail clients that strive for a similar user experience, support the basic convention of using asterisks for boldface and underscores for italic style.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] While Word removes the characters, Outlook retains them.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] In HTML, removed or deleted and inserted text is marked up with the `<del>` and `<ins>` element types, respectively.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] However, legacy element types `<s>` or `<strike>` and `<u>` are still also available for stricken and underlined spans of text.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] AsciiDoc, ATX, Creole, MediaWiki, PmWiki, reST, Slack, Textile and WhatsApp do not support dedicated markup for underlining text.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] Textile does, however, support insertion via the `+inserted+` syntax.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] ATX, Creole, MediaWiki, PmWiki, reST and Setext do not support dedicated markup for striking through text.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] DokuWiki supports HTML-like `<del>stricken</del>` syntax, even with embedded HTML disabled.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] AsciiDoc supports stricken text through a built-in *text span* prefix: `[.line-through]#stricken#`.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] Quoted computer code is traditionally presented in typewriter-like fonts where each character occupies the same fixed width.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] HTML offers the semantic `<code>` and the deprecated, presentational `<tt>` element types for this task.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] The second style is based on repeated markers (e.g., hash `#`, equals `=` or asterisk `*`) at the start of the heading itself, where the number of repetitions indicates the (sometimes inverse) heading level.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] Most languages also support the reduplication of the markers at the end of the line, but whereas some make them mandatory, others do not even expect their numbers to match.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] Org-mode supports indentation as a means of indicating the level.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] BBCode does not support section headings at all.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] POD and Textile choose the HTML convention of numbered heading levels instead.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] Microsoft Word supports auto-formatting paragraphs as headings if they do not contain more than a handful of words, no period at the end and the user hits the enter key twice.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] For lower levels, the user may press the tabulator key the according number of times before entering the text, i.e., one through eight tabs for heading levels two through nine.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] Hyperlinks can either be added inline, which may clutter the code because of long URLs, or with named `alias` or numbered `id` references to lines containing nothing but the address and related attributes and often may be located anywhere in the document.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] Most languages allow the author to specify text `Text` to be displayed instead of the plain address `http://example.com` and some also provide methods to set a different link title `Title` which may contain more information about the destination.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] LMLs that are tailored for special setups, e.g., wikis or code documentation, may automatically generate named anchors (for headings, functions etc.) inside the document, link to related pages (possibly in a different namespace) or provide a textual search for linked keywords.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] Most languages employ (double) square or angular brackets to surround links, but hardly any two languages are completely compatible.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] Many can automatically recognize and parse absolute URLs inside the text without further markup.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] Gemtext and setext links must be on a line by themselves, they cannot be used inline.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] Org-mode's normal link syntax does a text search of the file.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] You can also put in dedicated targets with `<<id>>`.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] HTML requires an explicit element for the list, specifying its type, and one for each list item, but most lightweight markup languages need only different line prefixes for the bullet points or enumerated items.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] Some languages rely on indentation for nested lists, others use repeated parent list markers.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] Microsoft Word automatically converts paragraphs that start with an asterisk `*`, hyphen-minus `-` or greater-than bracket `>` followed by a space or horizontal tabulator as bullet list items.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] Languages differ on whether they support optional or mandatory digits in numbered list items, which kinds of enumerators they understand (e.g., decimal digit *1*, roman numerals *i* or *I*, alphabetic letters *a* or *A*) and whether they support to keep explicit values in the output format.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] Some Markdown dialects, for instance, will respect a start value other than 1, but ignore any other explicit value.
[src:restructuredtext/lightweight-markup-language] Slack assists the user in entering enumerated and bullet lists, but does not actually format them as such, i.e., it just includes a leading digit followed by a period and a space or a bullet character `•` in front of a line.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] A **markup language** is a text-encoding system which specifies the structure and formatting of a document and potentially the relationships among its parts.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Markup can control the display of a document or enrich its content to facilitate automated processing.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] A markup language is a set of rules governing what markup information may be included in a document and how it is combined with the content of the document in a way to facilitate use by humans and computer programs.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] The idea and terminology evolved from the marking up of paper manuscripts (e.g., with revision instructions by editors), traditionally written with a red pen or blue pencil on authors' manuscripts.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Older markup languages, which typically focus on typesetting and presentation, include troff, TeX, and LaTeX.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Scribe and most modern markup languages, such as XML, identify document components (for example headings, paragraphs, and tables), with the expectation that technology, such as stylesheets, will be used to apply formatting or other processing.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Some markup languages, such as the widely used HTML, have pre-defined presentation semantics, meaning that their specifications prescribe some aspects of how to present the structured data on particular media.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] HTML, like DocBook, Open eBook, JATS, and many others, are based on the markup metalanguages XML and SGML.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] That is, SGML and XML allow designers to specify particular schemas, which determine which elements, attributes, and other features are permitted, and where.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] A key characteristic of most markup languages is that they allow combining markup with content such as text and pictures.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] For example, if a few words in a sentence need to be emphasized, or identified as a proper name, defined term, or another special item, the markup may be inserted between the characters of the sentence.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] The word *markup* is derived from the traditional publishing practice of *marking up* a manuscript, which involves adding handwritten annotations in the form of conventional symbolic printer's instructions—in the margins and text of a paper or printed manuscript.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] For centuries, this task was done primarily by skilled typographers known as *markup men* or *markers* who marked up text to indicate what typeface, style, and size should be applied to each part, and then passed the manuscript to others for typesetting by hand or machine.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] The markup was also commonly applied by editors, proofreaders, publishers, and graphic designers, and by authors themselves, all of whom might also mark things such as corrections and changes.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] There are three general categories of electronic markup, articulated by James Coombs, Allen Renear, and Steven DeRose in 1987, and Tim Bray in 2003.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Presentational markup is used by traditional word-processing systems.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Binary codes embedded within document text produce the WYSIWYG ('what you see is what you get') effect.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Such markup is usually hidden from human users, even authors and editors.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Such systems use procedural and descriptive markup internally but convert them to present the user with formatted arrangements of type.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Markup is embedded in text which provides instructions for programs to process the text.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Well-known examples include troff, TeX, and Markdown.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Generally, software processes the text sequentially from beginning to end, following the instructions as encountered.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Such text is often edited with the markup visible and directly manipulated by the author.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Popular procedural markup systems usually include programming constructs, especially macros, allowing complex sets of instructions to be invoked by a simple name (and perhaps a few parameters).
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] This is much faster, less error-prone, and more maintenance-friendly than re-stating the same or similar instructions in many places.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Descriptive markup is specifically used to describe parts of the document for what they are, rather than how they should be processed.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Well-known systems that provide many such labels include LaTeX, HTML, and XML.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] The objective is to decouple the structure of the document from any particular treatment or rendition of it.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Such markup is often described as *semantic*.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] An example of a descriptive markup is HTML's `<cite>` tag, which is used to label a citation.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Descriptive markup—sometimes called *logical markup* or *conceptual markup*—encourages authors to write in a way that describes the material conceptually, rather than visually.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] There is considerable overlap and concurrent use of markup types.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] In modern word-processing systems, presentational markup is often saved in descriptive-markup-oriented systems such as XML, and then processed procedurally by implementations.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] The programming in procedural-markup systems, such as TeX, may be used to create higher-level markup systems that are more descriptive in nature, such as LaTeX.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] In recent years, several markup languages have been developed with ease of use as a key goal, and without input from standards organizations, aimed at allowing authors to create formatted text via web browsers, for example in wikis and web forums.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] These are sometimes called lightweight markup languages.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Markdown, BBCode, and the markup language used by Wikipedia are examples of such languages.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] The first well-known public presentation of markup languages in computer text processing was made by William W.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Tunnicliffe at a conference in 1967, although he preferred to call it *generic coding.* It can be seen as a response to the emergence of processing programs such as RUNOFF that each used their own control notation, often specific to the target typesetting device.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] In the 1970s, Tunnicliffe led the development of a standard called GenCode for the publishing industry.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Book designer Stanley Rice published speculation along similar lines in 1970.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Brian Reid, in his 1980 dissertation at Carnegie Mellon University, developed a theory and working implementation of descriptive markup in actual use.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] However, IBM researcher Charles Goldfarb is more commonly considered the inventor of markup languages.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Goldfarb developed the basic idea while working on a primitive document management system intended for law firms in 1969, and helped invent IBM's Generalized Markup Language (GML) later that same year.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] GML was first publicly disclosed in 1973.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] In 1975, Goldfarb moved from Cambridge, Massachusetts to Silicon Valley and became a product planner at the IBM Almaden Research Center.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] There, he convinced IBM's executives to deploy GML commercially in 1978 as part of IBM's Document Composition Facility product, and it was widely used in business within a few years.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Standard Generalized Markup Language (SGML), the first standard descriptive markup language, was based on both GML and GenCode.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] It was the result of an International Organization for Standardization (ISO) committee that was first chaired by Tunnicliffe, and which Goldfarb also worked on beginning in 1974.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Goldfarb eventually became chair of the committee.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] SGML was first released by ISO as the ISO 8879 standard in October 1986.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Some early examples of computer markup languages available outside the publishing industry can be found in typesetting tools on Unix systems such as troff and nroff.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] In these systems, formatting commands were inserted into the document text so that typesetting software could format the text according to the editor's specifications.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] It was a trial and error iterative process to correctly print a document.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] The availability of WYSIWYG publishing software supplanted much use of these languages among casual users, though professional publishing work still uses markup to specify the non-visual structure of texts, and WYSIWYG editors now usually save documents in a markup-language-based format.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Another major publishing standard is TeX, created and refined by Donald Knuth in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] TeX concentrated on the detailed layout of text and font descriptions to typeset mathematical books.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] This required Knuth to spend considerable time investigating the art of typesetting.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] TeX is mainly used in academia, where it is a *de facto* standard in many scientific disciplines.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] A TeX macro package known as LaTeX provides a descriptive markup system on top of TeX, and is widely used both among the scientific community and the publishing industry.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] The first language to make a clear distinction between structure and presentation was Scribe, developed by Brian Reid and described in his doctoral thesis in 1980.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Scribe was revolutionary in a number of ways, introducing the idea of styles separated from the marked-up document, and a grammar that controlled the usage of descriptive elements.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Scribe influenced the development of GML and later SGML, and is a direct ancestor to HTML and LaTeX.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] In the early 1980s, the idea that markup should focus on the structural aspects of a document and leave the visual presentation of that structure to the interpreter led to the creation of SGML.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] The language was developed by a committee chaired by Goldfarb.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] It incorporated ideas from many different sources, including Tunnicliffe's project, GenCode.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Sharon Adler, Anders Berglund, and James A.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Marke were also key members of the SGML committee.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] SGML specifies a syntax for including the markup in documents, as well as one for separately describing what tags are allowed, and where (the document type definition (DTD), later known as a schema).
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] This allows authors to create and use any markup they want, selecting tags that make the most sense to them and are named in their own natural languages, while also allowing automated verification.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Thus, SGML is properly a metalanguage, and many markup languages are derived from it.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] From the late 1980s onward, most substantial new markup languages have been based on SGML, including the Text Encoding Initiative (TEI) guidelines and DocBook.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] SGML was promulgated as the ISO 8879 standard in 1986.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] SGML found wide acceptance and use in fields with very large-scale documentation requirements.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] However, many found it cumbersome and difficult to learn—a side effect of its design attempting to do too much and being too flexible.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] For example, SGML made end tags (or start tags, or both) optional in certain contexts, because its developers thought markup would be done manually by overworked support staff who would appreciate saving keystrokes.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] In 1989, computer scientist Tim Berners-Lee wrote a memo proposing an Internet-based hypertext system, then specified HTML and wrote the browser and server software in late 1990.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] The first publicly available description of HTML was a document called "HTML Tags", first mentioned on the Internet by Berners-Lee in late 1991.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] It describes 18 elements comprising the initial, relatively simple design of HTML.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Except for the hyperlink tag, these were strongly influenced by SGMLguid, an in-house SGML-based documentation format at CERN, and very similar to the sample schema in the SGML standard.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Eleven of these elements still exist in HTML 4.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Berners-Lee considered HTML an SGML application.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) formally defined it as such with the mid-1993 publication of the first proposal for an HTML specification: "Hypertext Markup Language (HTML)" by Berners-Lee and Dan Connolly, which included an SGML DTD to define the grammar.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] These formatting commands were derived from those used by typesetters to manually format documents.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Steven DeRose argues that HTML's use of descriptive markup (and the influence of SGML in particular) was a major factor in the success of the Web, because of the flexibility and extensibility that it enabled.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] HTML became the main markup language for creating web pages and other information that can be displayed in a web browser and is likely the most used markup language in the world in the 21st century.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] XML (Extensible Markup Language) is a widely used meta markup language.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] It was developed by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) in a committee created and chaired by Jon Bosak.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] The main purpose of XML was to simplify SGML by focusing on a particular use case—documents on the Internet.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] XML remains a metalanguage like SGML, allowing users to create any tags needed (hence *extensible*) and then describing those tags and their permitted uses.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] XML adoption was hastened by the fact that every XML document can be written so that it is also an SGML document, allowing existing SGML users and software to switch to XML fairly easily.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] At the same time, XML eliminates many complex features of SGML to simplify implementation environments such as documents and publications.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] It appears to balance simplicity and flexibility, as well as support very robust schema definitions and validation tools, and was rapidly adopted for many uses.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] XML is now widely used for communicating data between applications, serializing program data, for hardware communication protocols, vector graphics, and other uses besides documents.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] From January 2000 until HTML 5 was released, all W3C recommendations for HTML were based on XML, using XHTML (Extensible HyperText Markup Language).
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] The language specification requires that XHTML documents be *well-formed* XML documents.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] This allows for more rigorous and robust documents, by avoiding many syntax errors which historically led to unwanted browser behavior, while still using document components familiar to HTML users.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Another difference is that all attribute values in tags must be quoted.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Both these differences are commonly criticized as verbose but also praised because they make it far easier to detect, localize, and repair errors.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Finally, all tag and attribute names within the XHTML namespace must be lowercase to be valid.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] HTML, on the other hand, was case-insensitive.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Many XML-based applications exist, including the Resource Description Framework as RDF/XML, XForms, DocBook, SOAP, and the Web Ontology Language (OWL).
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] For a partial list of these, see list of XML markup languages.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] A common feature of many markup languages is that they intermix the text of a document with markup instructions in the same data stream or file.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] This is not necessary; it is possible to isolate markup from text content, using pointers, offsets, IDs, or other methods to coordinate the two.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Such *standoff* markup is typical for the internal representations that programs use to work with marked-up documents.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] However, *embedded* or *inline* markup is much more common elsewhere.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] The codes enclosed in angle-brackets `<like this>` are markup instructions (known as *tags*), while the text between these instructions is the actual text of the document.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] The codes `h1`, `p`, and `em` are examples of *semantic* markup, in that they describe the intended purpose or the meaning of the text they include.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Specifically, `h1` means the enclosed text is a *first-level heading*, `p` means a *paragraph*, and `em` means an *emphasized* word or phrase.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] A program interpreting such structural markup may apply its own rules or styles for presenting the various pieces of text, using different typefaces, boldness, font size, indentation, color, or other styles, as desired.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] For example, a tag such as `h1` might be presented in a large bold sans-serif typeface in an article, or it might be underscored in a monospaced (fixed-width font) document, or it might not change the presentation at all.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] In contrast, the `i` tag in HTML 4 is an example of *presentational* markup, which is generally used to specify a characteristic of the text without specifying the reason for that appearance.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] In this case, the `i` element dictates the use of an italic typeface.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] However, in HTML 5, this element has been repurposed with a more semantic usage: to denote "a span of text in an alternate voice or mood, or otherwise offset from the normal prose in a manner indicating a different quality of text".
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] For example, it is appropriate to use the `i` element to indicate a taxonomic designation or a phrase in another language.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] The change was made to ease the transition from HTML 4 to 5 as smoothly as possible so that deprecated uses of presentational elements would preserve the most likely intended meaning.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] TEI has published extensive guidelines for how to encode texts of interest in the humanities and social sciences, developed through years of international cooperative work.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] These guidelines are used for encoding historical documents, and the works of particular scholars, periods, and genres.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] While the idea of markup language originated with text documents, they are increasingly used in the presentation of other types of information, including playlists, vector graphics, web services, content syndication, and user interfaces.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] Most of these are XML applications because XML is a well-defined and extensible language.
[src:restructuredtext/markup-language] The use of XML has also led to the possibility of combining multiple markup languages into a single profile, like XHTML+SMIL and XHTML+MathML+SVG.
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] This document has been placed in the public domain.
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] The text below contains links that look like "(quickref)".
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] These are relative links that point to the Quick reStructuredText user reference.
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] If these links don't work, please refer to the master quick reference document.
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] From the outset, let me say that "Structured Text" is probably a bit of a misnomer.
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] It's more like "Relaxed Text" that uses certain consistent patterns.
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] These patterns are interpreted by a HTML converter to produce "Very Structured Text" that can be used by a web browser.
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] The most basic pattern recognised is a **paragraph** (quickref).
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] That's a chunk of text that is separated by blank lines (one is enough).
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] Paragraphs must have the same indentation -- that is, line up at their left edge.
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] Paragraphs that start indented will result in indented quote paragraphs.
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] Inside paragraphs and other bodies of text, you may additionally mark text for *italics* with "*italics*" or **bold** with "**bold**".
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] If you want something to appear as a fixed-space literal, use "``double back-quotes``".
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] Note that no further fiddling is done inside the double back-quotes -- so asterisks "*" etc. are left alone.
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] If you find that you want to use one of the "special" characters in text, it will generally be OK -- reStructuredText is pretty smart.
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] For example, this lone asterisk * is handled just fine, as is the asterisk in this equation: 5*6=30.
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] If you actually want text *surrounded by asterisks* to **not** be italicised, then you need to indicate that the asterisk is not special.
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] Lists of items come in three main flavours: **enumerated**, **bulleted** and **definitions**.
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] In all list cases, you may have as many paragraphs, sublists, etc. as you want, as long as the left-hand side of the paragraph or whatever aligns with the first line of text in the list item.
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] Lists must always start a new paragraph -- that is, they must appear after a blank line.
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] Start a line off with a number or letter followed by a period ".", right bracket ")" or surrounded by brackets "( )" -- whatever you're comfortable with.
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] 2. make sure the numbers are in the correct sequence though!
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] Unlike the other two, the definition lists consist of a term, and the definition of that term.
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] Definition lists associate a term with a definition.
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] The term is a one-line phrase, and the definition is one or more paragraphs or body elements, indented relative to the term.
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] Blank lines are not allowed between term and definition.
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] To just include a chunk of preformatted, never-to-be-fiddled-with text, finish the prior paragraph with "::".
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] The preformatted block is finished when the text falls back to the same indentation level as a paragraph prior to the preformatted block.
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] To break longer text up into sections, you use **section headers**.
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] These are a single line of text (one or more words) with adornment: an underline alone, or an underline and an overline together, in dashes "-----", equals "======", tildes "~~~~~~" or any of the non-alphanumeric characters = - ` : ' " ~ ^ _ * + # < > that you feel comfortable with.
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] An underline-only adornment is distinct from an overline-and-underline adornment using the same character.
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] The underline/overline must be at least as long as the title text.
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] (Pseudo-XML uses indentation for nesting and has no end-tags.
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] It's not possible to show actual processed output, as in the other examples, because sections cannot exist inside block quotes.
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] Note that section headers are available as link targets, just using their name.
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] To link to the Lists heading, I write "Lists_".
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] If the heading has a space in it like text styles, we need to quote the heading "`text styles`_".
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] The title of the whole document is distinct from section titles and may be formatted somewhat differently (e.g. the HTML writer by default shows it as a centered heading).
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] To indicate the document title in reStructuredText, use a section title with unique adornment style at the beginning of the document.
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] To indicate the document subtitle, use another unique adornment style immediately after the document title.
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] Note that "Document Title" and "Section Title" above both use equals signs, but are distict and unrelated styles.
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] The text of overline-and-underlined titles (but not underlined-only) may be inset for aesthetics.
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] To include an image in your document, you use the the image directive.
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] The images/biohazard.png part indicates the filename of the image you wish to appear in the document.
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] There's no restriction placed on the image (format, size etc).
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] See the full image directive documentation for more info.
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] This primer introduces the most common features of reStructuredText, but there are a lot more to explore.
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] The Quick reStructuredText user reference is a good place to go next.
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] For complete details, the reStructuredText Markup Specification is the place to go [1].
[src:restructuredtext/quickstart] Users who have questions or need assistance with Docutils or reStructuredText should post a message to the Docutils-users mailing list.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext-basics] reStructuredText is the default plaintext markup language used by Sphinx.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext-basics] This section is a brief introduction to reStructuredText (reST) concepts and syntax, intended to provide authors with enough information to author documents productively.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext-basics] Since reStructuredText was designed to be a simple, unobtrusive markup language, this will not take too long.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext-basics] The authoritative reStructuredText User Documentation.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext-basics] The “ref” links in this document link to the description of the individual constructs in the reStructuredText reference.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext-basics] The paragraph (ref) is the most basic block in a reStructuredText document.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext-basics] Paragraphs are simply chunks of text separated by one or more blank lines.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext-basics] As in Python, indentation is significant in reStructuredText, so all lines of the same paragraph must be left-aligned to the same level of indentation.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext-basics] If asterisks or backquotes appear in running text and could be confused with inline markup delimiters, they have to be escaped with a backslash.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext-basics] These restrictions may be lifted in future versions of the docutils.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext-basics] It is also possible to replace or expand upon some of this inline markup with roles.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext-basics] List markup (ref) is natural: just place an asterisk at the start of a paragraph and indent properly.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext-basics] Note that the term cannot have more than one line of text.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext-basics] Quoted paragraphs (ref) are created by just indenting them more than the surrounding paragraphs.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext-basics] Literal code blocks (ref) are introduced by ending a paragraph with the special marker `::`.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext-basics] That way, the second sentence in the above example’s first paragraph would be rendered as “The next paragraph is a code sample:”.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext-basics] Code highlighting can be enabled for these literal blocks on a document-wide basis using the `highlight` directive and on a project-wide basis using the `highlight_language` configuration option.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext-basics] The `code-block` directive can be used to set highlighting on a block-by-block basis.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext-basics] Doctest blocks (ref) are interactive Python sessions cut-and-pasted into docstrings.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext-basics] They do not require the literal blocks syntax.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext-basics] For *grid tables* (ref), you have to “paint” the cell grid yourself.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext-basics] Two more syntaxes are supported: *CSV tables* and *List tables*.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext] It is part of the Docutils project of the Python Doc-SIG (Documentation Special Interest Group), aimed at creating a set of tools for Python similar to Javadoc for Java or Plain Old Documentation (POD) for Perl.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext] Docutils can extract comments and information from Python programs, and format them into various forms of program documentation.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext] In this sense, reStructuredText is a lightweight markup language designed to be both processable by documentation-processing software such as Docutils, and be easily readable by human programmers who are reading and writing Python source code.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext] reStructuredText evolved from an earlier lightweight markup language called StructuredText (developed by Zope).
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext] There were a number of problems with StructuredText, and reST was developed to address them.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext] Parts of the reST syntax were inspired by the Setext language from the early 1990s.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext] Elements of the common RFC822 Internet Message Format and Javadoc formats were also considered for inclusion in the design.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext] reStructuredText was first released in June 2001.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext] It began to see significant use in the Python community in 2002.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext] The reference implementation of the reST parser is a component of the Docutils text processing framework in the Python programming language, but other parsers are available.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext] The Docutils project has not registered any MIME type for reStructuredText nor designated any unregistered MIME type as official, but documents the MIME type `text/x-rst` as in *de facto* use by, for example, the build system for the Python website.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext] The same MIME type is used in the freedesktop.org file type database used by desktop environments on Linux.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext] Another MIME type, `text/prs.fallenstein.rst`, was registered as a vanity MIME type by a third party in 2003 to represent reStructuredText, and remains the only IANA-registered MIME type for reStructuredText, although it is not acknowledged as such by the Docutils project.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext] reStructuredText is commonly used for technical documentation, for example, in documentation of Python libraries.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext] However, it is suitable for a wide range of texts.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext] Since 2008, reST has been a core component of Python's Sphinx document generation system.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext] Trac also supports reStructuredText, as do GitHub and Bitbucket.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext] In 2011, Distributed Proofreaders, which prepared texts for Project Gutenberg, was considering adoption of reST as a basic format from which other ebook formats could be generated.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext] In July 2016 the Linux kernel project decided to transition from DocBook based documentation to reStructuredText and the Sphinx toolchain.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext] The software build tool CMake switched from a custom markup language to reStructuredText in version 3.0 for its documentation.
[src:restructuredtext/restructuredtext] The JetBrains IDE ecosystem supports reStructuredText editing through plugins such as reStructuredText Pro, which provides RST and Sphinx documentation support including live preview and syntax highlighting.
[src:restructuredtext/rst] reStructuredText is an easy-to-read, what-you-see-is-what-you-get plaintext markup syntax and parser system.
[src:restructuredtext/rst] It is useful for in-line program documentation (such as Python docstrings), for quickly creating simple web pages, and for standalone documents. reStructuredText is designed for extensibility for specific application domains.
[src:restructuredtext/rst] The reStructuredText parser is a component of Docutils. reStructuredText is a revision and reinterpretation of the StructuredText and Setext lightweight markup systems.
[src:restructuredtext/rst] The primary goal of reStructuredText is to define and implement a markup syntax for use in Python docstrings and other documentation domains, that is readable and simple, yet powerful enough for non-trivial use.
[src:restructuredtext/rst] The intended purpose of the markup is the conversion of reStructuredText documents into useful structured data formats.
[src:restructuredtext/rst] See statemachine.py for an example of a Python module fully documented using reStructuredText.
[src:restructuredtext/rst] The following testimonials are excerpts from unsolicited posts to mailing lists and the comp.lang.python newsgroup.
[src:restructuredtext/rst] Being excerpts, there's often context missing, which sometimes tones down the message.
[src:restructuredtext/rst] This being the Internet, there were plenty of people opposed to the idea of reStructuredText, some vehemently.
[src:restructuredtext/rst] Discovering *those* gems is left as an exercise for the reader.
